  m_Name: Mushroom_18_Moonring
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::Hollowfen.Data.MushroomFieldGuideData
  _id: moonring
  _commonName: Moonring
  _latinName: Amanita virosa
  _edibility: 1
  _edibilityLabel: Deadly
  _description: "Sable's seedbook name for the Destroying Angel (Amanita virosa)
    \u2014 pure white, elegant, and among the deadliest mushrooms in the world. The
    old hand called it Moonring for the pale ring on its stem and the cap that seems
    to hold moonlight; the science is grimmer: the same liver-destroying amatoxins
    as the Death Cap."
  _idFeatures:
  - "Entirely pure white \u2014 cap, gills, stem, all white"
  - White free gills, never pink, never brown
  - "A white ring (annulus) on the upper stem \u2014 the moonring itself"
  - Bulbous sac-like volva at the base, often hidden in soil or moss
  - White spore print
  _habitat: "Mycorrhizal with broadleaf trees \u2014 birch, beech, oak; mixed woodland
    edges."
  _season: Mid-summer through autumn
  _lookalikes: Field Mushroom (Agaricus campestris) is EDIBLE but has pink or brown
    gills, never white, and no volva. The unchanging white gills are the universal
    warning.
  _notes: "With the Death Cap, this accounts for nearly all fatal mushroom poisonings
    in temperate regions. Delayed onset: six to twelve hours of nothing, then violent
    illness, a false recovery, then liver failure. Treat any all-white gilled mushroom
    with extreme suspicion. Sable's seedbook does not teach picking it \u2014 it
    teaches knowing it."
